				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I've got a question about the resolution of the NES vs. the resolution of the Super Nintendo:<br /><br />The NES is 256 x 240 while a standard NTSC TV typically just shows 256 x 224 of the pixels. But from a pure data point of view, it's 256 x 240 and you can make the additional rows visible in an emulator.<br />The Super Nintendo is 256 x 224 and even in an emulator, you see just that, not 256 x 240.<br /><br />So, does that mean that the Super Nintendo has a lower resolution than the NES?<br /><br />And if a TV cuts off some of the rows from the NES image, wouldn't that mean that the TV cuts off rows from the Super Nintendo image as well? And since the Super Nintendo has only 224 pixel rows natively, wouldn't that mean that the Super Nintendo image as shown by an NTSC TV screen is even less than 224 rows while the same TV screen does show 224 line of the NES's 240 lines?</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
